Deploying a Secure and Scalable Web Application Architecture in AWS

Project Overview

The project demonstrates deploying applications securely in a VPC with public and private subnets, auto-scaling groups, load balancers, NAT gateways, and a bastion host.

Step-by-Step Guide

Step 1: Create the VPC with Public and Private Subnets

  1. Navigate to the VPC Dashboard:

    • Open AWS Management Console.
    • Search for and select "VPC."

  2. Create a VPC:

    • Choose "Create VPC and More."
    • Configure:
      • VPC Name: AWS-Project.
      • IPv4 CIDR Block: Leave default (e.g., 10.0.0.0/16).
      • Availability Zones: Select two (e.g., us-east-1a, us-east-1b).
      • Public Subnets: Two public subnets in each availability zone.
      • Private Subnets: Two private subnets in each availability zone.

  3. Set Routing for Subnets:

    • Attach an Internet Gateway to the VPC.
    • Associate public subnets with a route table that includes the Internet Gateway.
    • Create a NAT Gateway in one public subnet and associate private subnets with a route table configured to use the NAT Gateway.

Step 2: Configure Auto-Scaling Group and Launch Template

  1. Create a Launch Template:

    • Navigate to the EC2 dashboard and select "Launch Templates."
    • Configure:
      • Name: Project-Launch-Template.
      • AMI: Choose Ubuntu (or your preferred OS).
      • Instance Type: t2.micro.
      • Key Pair: Select or create a key pair.
      • Security Group:
        • Allow SSH (Port 22) and application traffic (e.g., Port 80).
        • Associate with the VPC.

  2. Create an Auto-Scaling Group:

    • Go to "Auto-Scaling Groups."
    • Configure:
      • Attach the launch template.
      • Select the private subnets in both availability zones.
      • Set:
        • Desired Capacity: 2
        • Minimum Instances: 1
        • Maximum Instances: 4.


Step 3: Set Up the Bastion Host

  1. Launch an EC2 Instance:

    • Choose t2.micro instance type with Ubuntu AMI.
    • Place the instance in a public subnet.
    • Assign a public IP.

  2. Configure Security Group:

    • Allow SSH (Port 22) access from your IP address.

  3. SSH into the Bastion Host:

    • Use the key pair to SSH:
      ssh -i <Your-Key.pem> ubuntu@<Bastion-Host-Public-IP>

  4. Prepare for Private Instance Access:

    • Transfer the private key to the Bastion Host:
      scp -i <Your-Key.pem> <Your-Key.pem> ubuntu@<Bastion-Host-Public-IP>:~/

Step 4: Deploy the Application

  1. SSH into Private Instances via the Bastion Host:

    • From the Bastion Host:
      ssh -i <Your-Key.pem> ubuntu@<Private-Instance-Private-IP>

  2. Install a Simple HTTP Server:
    sudo apt install apache2 -y
    sudo systemctl start apache2
    sudo systemctl enable apache2

  3. Host a sample website by placing an index.html file in the servers root directory (e.g., /var/www/html for Apache).

Step 5: Create the Load Balancer

  1. Navigate to the Load Balancer Dashboard:

    • In the EC2 dashboard, choose "Load Balancers."

  2. Create an Application Load Balancer:

    • Configure:
      • Name: AWS-Project-ALB.
      • Type: Internet-facing.
      • Subnets: Choose the public subnets.
      • Security Group: Allow HTTP (Port 80).

  3. Set Up Target Groups:

    • Create a target group and attach private instances on Port 8000.

  4. Register Targets:

    • Verify both instances are healthy.!

Step 6: Test the Setup

  1. Access the Load Balancer:

    • Copy the Load Balancers DNS name.
    • Open it in a browser:
      http://<Load-Balancer-DNS>
    • You should see the content from the deployed application.

  2. Test Load Balancing:

    • Deploy a different application in the second instance.
    • Verify traffic alternates between the two applications.

Step 6: Access Load Balancer Using Public URL (Route 53)

  • Objective: Map a custom domain to the load balancer using Route 53.

    1. Register a domain name in Hostinger (Route 53 or use an existing one.)
    2. Create a hosted zone for the domain in Route 53.
    3. Add an A record (Alias) in the hosted zone that points to the load balancers DNS name.
    4. Verify that the custom domain resolves to the load balancer, and accessing it loads the web application hosted on the servers.




Tools and Services Used in This Project

AWS Services

  1. VPC: Isolated network for resources.
  2. Subnets: Public (for Load Balancer, NAT Gateway) and Private (for application servers).
  3. Internet Gateway: Enables internet access for public resources.
  4. NAT Gateway: Allows secure internet access for private resources.
  5. Route Tables: Manages traffic routing.
  6. Security Groups: Firewall rules for resource access.
  7. Bastion Host: Secure bridge to access private instances via SSH.
  8. EC2 Instances: Virtual servers for the application.
  9. Auto-Scaling Group: Automatically adjusts the number of instances.
  10. Application Load Balancer: Distributes incoming traffic across instances.

Tools

  1. AWS Management Console: GUI for managing AWS resources.
  2. SSH Client: Access EC2 instances (e.g., Terminal, PuTTY).
  3. SCP: Secure file transfer between local machine and EC2.
  4. Text Editor: Edit files on EC2 (e.g., Nano, Vim).
